And who could have beleived that these Priests of England were so far worse, then the Sons of Ely, who were Sons of Beliall, and knew not God; for they would take but the Tithe and Offerings by voice, but these Priests take the Tithe, and Offerings, and much more, and the bodyes of men, and women also, and keepe them in prison untill death, for whom they doe no work, and who desires none of their ministry, and if they herein be not worse then the Sons of Beliall, let all sober minded judge, and consider this thing w • th me, that the first Priests that caused their servants to take the offerings by force know not God, then say I, Alas alas for the Priest of England, are they so much •… then those that knew not God, how doe their shame appeare, and who could have beleived that those Priests were worse then Iudas, that was a Devill, who b • ought the mony againe that he had received, but when doe these Priests, being again the mony and goods, which they have received and tak • n away by force (though Iudas did not take his mony by force) and how hard are these words to be received by such who have not yet come to see and understand these things, and how unwilling will the Priests themselves be, to beleive the truth of this which I have thus weighed, and considered, and pondered in the meditations of my mind, what horrible things from the 〈◊〉 darknesse are these, that the Priests should be worse then Iudas, for after he had betrayed the innocent, he confessed he had sinned, and brought back the mony, but the Priests said what is that to us; and are not these Preists worse then they; for these doe not onely cause the be • raying of the innocent, and say what is that to us, but they take mony, and f • rce people to give them large mony, for betraying that which is innocent in them, by their subtilty, and craftinesse, whereby they lye in waite to deceive;
and when they have betrayed the innocent principle of God in people, by telling them it will deceive them, yet they will not bring the peoples mony back as Iudas did, nor so much as confesse they have sinned therein, but are Impudent. O hard hearted and unreasonable men, have I said what shall be said unto them, surely they are the worst of men, and it had been good for them, they had never been born. Or had a being upon the earth; did the Prophet mourne over or cry aloud unto them, that spent their mony and labour, for that which satisfieth not, oh what shall I then say or write, or how shall I cry loud enough or mourn enough yet more in secret, or sound a trumpet, to these dead sleepy Priests, who compell people to give them so much mony, or spoile their goods, and imprison their bodyes till death, for that which is so f •… from satisfying them, that their soules are murthered thereby, and the innocent •… thing in them betrayed, and the witnesse denyed: oh who can with hold from declar •
ing this, and who can but write it in a booke; that they may see the state which they are in, and that people may know them by their fruits, which did never so planely appeare as now.
